Subject:    <a href="?t=95837886900045&r=1&w=2">Recognizing .arpa or not</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837661900001&r=1&w=2">sun!l5!gnu () Berkeley (John Gilmore)</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198503">1985-03-12 15:23:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426376&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426376&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I complained to an Arpanet postmaster about his mailer not recognizing
the name "sail.arpa".  Here's the response...

------- Forwarded Message

Date: 11 Mar 85  1755 PST
From: Martin Frost &lt;ME@SU-AI.ARPA&gt;
Subject: domain names   
To: sun!l5!gnu@BERKELEY

    For some reason Sail's mailer doesn't know its own name.
    If you are going to support the alias "sail" you should support
    it everywhere.  Or wipe it out everywhere.  The current situation is
    just confusing.

       ----- Transcript of session follows -----
    &gt;&gt;&gt; RCPT To:&lt;gio@sail.ARPA&gt;
    &lt;&lt;&lt; 550 I'm not host "SAIL.ARPA", in "RCPT To:&lt;gio@sail.ARPA&gt;"
    550 gio@sail.arpa... User unknown

To my knowledge, domain names are not yet implemented or required in
the Internet, so we recognize exactly those versions of our host name
that are registered with the NIC: SU-AI.ARPA, SU-AI, SAIL, and SUAI.

SAIL.ARPA is not one of these.

------- End of Forwarded Message

Unfortunately when somebody tells me to send to "GIO@SAIL", I have to
add ".arpa" to get it from MY network into HIS network.  I don't have
access to any NIC databases to tell me that "SAIL" really means
"SU-AI.ARPA".

I thought the domain plan was far enough along that everybody on the
Arpanet had to recognize and strip ".arpa" if they couldn't deal with
it properly.  Here's a small quote from a "Draft" RFC of a year ago:

RFC DRAFT                                                  February 1984
Domain Implementation Schedule

Policy Statement

   The names of hosts will be changed to domain style names.  Hosts will
   begin to use domain style names on 7-Mar-84, and the use of old style
   names will be completely phased out before 2-May-84.

   This applies to both the ARPA research hosts and the DDN operational
   hosts.

